====================================================================
üìå DATA MODELS IN DBMS (NOTES + EXAMPLES)
====================================================================

A Data Model defines HOW data is structured, stored, organized,
and manipulated in a database system.

It acts as a **blueprint** for designing databases.

====================================================================
WHY DO WE USE DATA MODELS?
--------------------------------------------------------------------
‚úî To represent real-world data logically  
‚úî To define relationships between data  
‚úî To ensure data consistency & integrity  
‚úî To simplify database design  
‚úî To support efficient data storage & retrieval  

====================================================================
TYPES OF DATA MODELS IN DBMS
--------------------------------------------------------------------
1Ô∏è‚É£ Hierarchical Data Model  
2Ô∏è‚É£ Network Data Model  
3Ô∏è‚É£ Relational Data Model  
4Ô∏è‚É£ Entity-Relationship (ER) Model  
5Ô∏è‚É£ Object-Oriented Data Model  

====================================================================
# 1Ô∏è‚É£ HIERARCHICAL DATA MODEL
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Data is organized in a **tree-like structure** with
Parent ‚Üí Child relationship.

‚úî One parent  
‚úî Many children  
‚úî Top-down access  

Example:
Company ‚Üí Department ‚Üí Employee  

ADVANTAGES:
‚úî Simple structure  
‚úî Fast data access  

DISADVANTAGES:
‚ùå No many-to-many relationship  
‚ùå Rigid structure  

====================================================================
# 2Ô∏è‚É£ NETWORK DATA MODEL
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Data is organized using a **graph structure** where
a record can have multiple parents and children.

Example:
Student ‚Üî Course  

ADVANTAGES:
‚úî Supports many-to-many relationships  
‚úî More flexible than hierarchical  

DISADVANTAGES:
‚ùå Complex structure  
‚ùå Difficult to maintain  

====================================================================
# 3Ô∏è‚É£ RELATIONAL DATA MODEL (MOST USED)
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Data is stored in **tables (relations)** with rows and columns.

‚úî Rows ‚Üí Records  
‚úî Columns ‚Üí Attributes  

Example:
STUDENT(student_id, name, age)

KEYS:
‚úî Primary Key  
‚úî Foreign Key  

ADVANTAGES:
‚úî Simple & powerful  
‚úî Data integrity  
‚úî Easy to query using SQL  

DISADVANTAGES:
‚ùå Performance issues with very large data  

====================================================================
# 4Ô∏è‚É£ ENTITY-RELATIONSHIP (ER) MODEL
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
A **conceptual model** used to design database structure
before implementation.

COMPONENTS:
‚úî Entity  
‚úî Attribute  
‚úî Relationship  

Example:
STUDENT ‚Äî ENROLLS ‚Äî COURSE  

USE:
‚úî Database design phase  
‚úî ER diagrams  

====================================================================
# 5Ô∏è‚É£ OBJECT-ORIENTED DATA MODEL
# ---------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Data is stored as **objects** similar to OOP concepts.

Features:
‚úî Classes  
‚úî Objects  
‚úî Inheritance  
‚úî Encapsulation  

Example:
Class Student { name, marks }

ADVANTAGES:
‚úî Suitable for complex data  
‚úî Supports multimedia  

DISADVANTAGES:
‚ùå Complex  
‚ùå Less commonly used  

====================================================================
REAL-WORLD USAGE
--------------------------------------------------------------------
‚úî Hierarchical ‚Üí File systems  
‚úî Network ‚Üí Telecom systems  
‚úî Relational ‚Üí MySQL, Oracle, SQL Server  
‚úî ER Model ‚Üí Database design  
‚úî Object-Oriented ‚Üí Multimedia & CAD  

====================================================================
SUMMARY
====================================================================

‚úî Data Models define structure of data  
‚úî ER Model is for design  
‚úî Relational Model is most popular  
‚úî Keys & relationships ensure integrity  
‚úî Data models help build efficient DBMS  

